		<header>
			
			<h1>WTO members square up for December ministerial </h1>

			
			<h4>
												28 November 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>With the eighth WTO Ministerial Conference due to take place from 15–17 December, members are airing alternative strategies for advancing the stalled Doha process. WTO Director-General Pascal Lamy has proposed to move ahead in subjects ‘where progress can be achieved, by reaching agreements on specific issues’ before weaving them into the full set of issues in the talks — the ‘single undertaking’. But this approach, which has the support of some industrialised countries, has provoked strong criticisms from a number of other members.</p><p>At the root of the problem is that the members are divided over what would be in the ‘early harvest’. Less Developed Countries (LDCs) want to see finalisation and implementation of duty-free, quota-free access for their exports to the markets of all the industrialised countries and some&nbsp; advanced developing countries. The Mauritian ambassador, the ACP coordinator at the WTO, is reported to have stressed the importance of resolving issues of implementing enhanced flexibilities for developing and poor countries that arose from the previous Uruguay Round. The EU, in contrast, is reported to be seeking early agreements on trade facilitation, improvements in the Dispute Settlement Understanding and progress of a range of 21<sup>st</sup> century issues before resolving what is already on the table. An early resolution of these differences appears unlikely.</p><p>At a sectoral level, two groups of members have presented separate proposals on the controversial issue of agricultural export restrictions. One proposal supported by the EU, Costa Rica, Singapore, and Switzerland&nbsp; among others (but not by Argentina, Brazil, China, India and South Africa, or by the USA)&nbsp; favours more far-reaching disciplines. It picks up the agreement by G20 agriculture ministers in June 2011 to respond to the global food crisis (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘G20 agriculture ministers agreed on action plan on high food prices’, August 2011) by removing food export restrictions or extraordinary taxes on humanitarian aid purchased by the UN World Food Programme, and proposes that WTO members adopt a similar commitment. Although such a ministerial declaration would not be legally binding, it might be taken into consideration by a dispute settlement panel, though trade officials have questioned whether any such issue would ever be subject to a dispute.</p><p>The other proposal is by a group of net food-importing developing countries (NFIDCs) and calls for a work programme to mitigate the impact of food price volatility on LDCs and NFIDCs. It proposes a comprehensive work programme to:</p>
<ul>

<li>ensure that such states can access adequate supplies of basic foodstuffs; </li>

<li>ensure that members ‘explore the possibility’ of developing rules to exempt countries in these two groups from export restrictions imposed by other WTO members that are major exporters of these foodstuffs; </li>

<li>help NFIDCs and LDCs to access trade financing on concessional terms, possibly through a fund that would be set up for this purpose.</li>

</ul>

		
		
