<a href="http://www.odi.org.uk/resources/download/6055.pdf" target="_self">http://www.odi.org.uk/resources/download/6055.pdf</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>As preparations are made for the WTO Ministerial in December, the influential economic research organisation, CEPII, has published a study that forecasts an increase in world exports of US$359 billion annually from a Doha deal (with further gains of $146 billion annually if&nbsp; there is also liberalisation of chemicals, machinery, and electronics). Such forecasts provide a plausible estimate of the relative aggregate gains from reducing barriers to trade. But both the words ‘relative’ and ‘aggregate’ are important.</p><p>The gains, though not insubstantial, are clearly of a lower order than the costs that could arise if the mounting crises faced by the world economy are not successfully resolved. Research by ODI, for example, has shown that a number of low-income countries could be very badly hit by the crisis in the euro zone. While a Doha deal and resolution of the crises are complementary rather than alternatives, it is the latter, resolution of the crises, that is likely to absorb decision-makers’ attention in the immediate future.</p><p>This matters, because the forecast gains from the Doha Development Round are an aggregate. The forecasts do not imply that everyone will gain on every item (or even from the entire Doha package). Rather, what the forecast shows is that the gainers will gain sufficient to make it worth their while to compensate the losers in order to secure agreement on a deal. But, so far, striking such a deal has eluded the WTO negotiators.</p><p>The December WTO Ministerial might move the negotiations forward, but the signs so far are not promising. The fundamental problem for the ACP is that their influence within the WTO is asymmetric. While they face major problems compared to the rich countries, they are able – especially if they form alliances – to block unwelcome changes within the WTO. But they cannot force other countries to accept their agenda – nor prevent states from making bilateral and plurilateral deals that may affect their interests outside the WTO. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
